ðŸ“– **Description:**
    The `grepdiff` command helps you search through the changes in a diff file (created by `diff`) based on a specific pattern.  It allows you to find lines that have been added or removed that contain a specific word or statement. This is very useful for finding relevant changes in large patches.

âš™ï¸ **Options:**
    ðŸ”¹ `--text`  --> ðŸ“„ Treat all files as text, even binary files, and search them.
    ðŸ”¹ `-p`  --> ðŸ” Only show diff lines that match the pattern in added or removed files.
    ðŸ”¹ `-i`  --> ðŸ”¤ Ignore case distinctions (case-insensitive).
    ðŸ”¹ `-n`  --> ðŸ”¢ Show line numbers with the results.

ðŸ›  **Examples:**

    $ grepdiff -p 'function my_function' mypatch.diff

    ðŸ”¹ This command displays all changes that add or remove the line 'function my_function' from the `mypatch.diff` file.

    $ grepdiff -i 'error message' mypatch.diff

    ðŸ”¹ This command searches for 'error message' in the changes, ignoring case.

âœ… **Simple Example:**

